a distinction between ancient and modern. The former is understood as a way of life which focuses on enquiry, whereas the latter is taken to be an epistemological approach which focuses on doubt. The studies in Sceptical Paths not only deepen the understanding of these approaches, but also show how ancient sceptical ideas find their way into modern thought, and modern sceptical ideas are anticipated in ancient thought. Within this state of affairs, the presence of sceptical arguments within Medieval philosophy is reflected in full force, not only enriching the historical narrative, but also introducing another layer to the sceptical discourse, namely its employment within theological settings. The various studies in this book exhibit the rich variety of expression in which scepticism manifests itself within various context and set against various philosophical and religious doctrines, schools, and approaches.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aBelief and doubtvCongresses. 0aKnowledge, Theory ofvCongresses. 0aSkepticismvCongresses. 4aJüdische Philosophie. 4aMittelalterliche Philosophie. 4aPhilosophie der Frühen Neuzeit. 4aSkeptizismus. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aJewish philosophy.  aScepticism.  aearly modern philosophy.  amedieval philosophy.1 aCharles, Sébastien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEichner, Heidrun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaliva, Racheli, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarvey, Warren Zev, econtributor.4ctb4https:/